<body>

    <h1>Recursive Fractal Tree Generator</h1>

    <div id="controls">
        <label for="depthSlider">Recursion Depth:</label>
        <input type="range" id="depthSlider" min="1" max="12" value="6">
        <span id="depthValue">6</span>
    </div>

    <canvas id="fractalCanvas" width="800" height="600"></canvas>

    <div id="explanation">
        <h2>Understanding Recursion Depth and Stack Overflow</h2>

        <p>This fractal tree beautifully illustrates the power of <strong>recursion</strong>, where a function calls itself to solve smaller instances of the same problem. Each "branch" draws itself and then recursively calls itself to draw its sub-branches. However, this elegant approach comes with important considerations, especially regarding <strong>recursion depth</strong>.</p>

        <h3>What is Recursion Depth?</h3>
        <p>Recursion depth refers to the number of times a recursive function calls itself before reaching a base case (a condition that stops the recursion). In our fractal tree, a depth of '1' means only the main trunk is drawn. A depth of '2' means the trunk and its immediate two branches are drawn, and so on. As the depth increases, the number of branches (and thus the number of function calls) grows exponentially.</p>

        <p>Each time a function is called, information about that call (its local variables, parameters, and where to return to after it finishes) is stored on a special memory area called the <strong>call stack</strong>. This stack operates on a Last-In, First-Out (LIFO) principle.</p>

        <h3>The Risk of Stack Overflow</h3>
        <p>The call stack has a finite size, determined by the operating system and programming language runtime. If a recursive function calls itself too many times without reaching a base case, or if the recursion depth exceeds the call stack's capacity, it will lead to a runtime error known as a <strong>Stack Overflow</strong>.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>How it happens:</strong> Each recursive call adds a new "frame" to the call stack. If the stack grows too large, it "overflows" its allocated memory space.</li>
            <li><strong>Consequences:</strong> The program typically crashes, often with an error message like "Maximum call stack size exceeded" (in JavaScript) or similar stack overflow errors in other languages. This is a critical error that can halt an application.</li>
            <li><strong>In our example:</strong> While a depth of 12 is usually safe for this simple tree in modern browsers, imagine if the slider went to 1000 or more. Each call to `drawBranch` adds to the stack. Eventually, the browser would likely crash or throw an error.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Practical Solutions to Deep Recursion and Stack Overflow</h3>
        <p>When faced with problems that naturally lend themselves to recursion but might involve very deep recursion, developers employ several strategies:</p>

        <h4>1. Tail Call Optimization (TCO)</h4>
        <p>Some languages and environments can optimize "tail calls" – where the recursive call is the very last operation in the function. In such cases, the current stack frame can be reused for the new call, preventing the stack from growing. JavaScript, however, does <strong>not guarantee</strong> TCO for general recursion (though it was briefly supported in strict mode ES6, it's largely deprecated due to compatibility issues).</p>
        <div class="code-snippet">
            <pre><code>// Example of a tail-recursive function (if TCO were guaranteed)
function factorial(n, acc = 1) {
    if (n === 0) return acc;
    return factorial(n - 1, acc * n); // Tail call
}</code></pre>
        </div>

        <h4>2. Iterative Conversion (Loop-based Solutions)</h4>
        <p>The most common and robust solution is to convert the recursive algorithm into an iterative one using loops. This often involves managing your own "stack" or "queue" data structure to keep track of the tasks that still need to be processed, rather than relying on the call stack.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>How it works:</strong> Instead of calling itself, the function pushes the necessary parameters for the next "recursive" step onto a custom array (acting as a stack or queue). A loop then processes items from this custom data structure until it's empty.</li>
            <li><strong>Advantages:</strong> Avoids stack overflow, offers better performance in many cases, and provides more explicit control over memory usage.</li>
            <li><strong>Disadvantages:</strong> Can sometimes be less intuitive or harder to read than a naturally recursive solution, especially for complex problems.</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="code-snippet">
            <pre><code>// Pseudocode for iterative fractal tree drawing
function drawTreeIterative(initialBranch) {
    let stack = [initialBranch];
    while (stack.length > 0) {
        let currentBranch = stack.pop(); // Or shift() for breadth-first
        // Draw currentBranch
        // If currentBranch has children:
            // stack.push(child1);
            // stack.push(child2);
    }
}</code></pre>
        </div>

        <h4>3. Limiting Recursion Depth (Practical Cap)</h4>
        <p>As demonstrated in this example, a simple and effective solution for many practical applications is to impose a hard limit on the recursion depth. This prevents accidental stack overflows when the problem naturally has a maximum reasonable depth. Our slider limits the depth to 12, which is visually complex enough without risking browser issues.</p>

        <h4>4. Trampolines (for JavaScript)</h4>
        <p>A "trampoline" is a technique used in JavaScript to simulate tail-call optimization for deeply recursive functions. It involves modifying the recursive function to return another function (a "thunk") instead of directly recurring. A trampoline function then repeatedly calls these thunks until a non-function value is returned. This effectively turns stack-heavy recursion into a loop.</p>
        <div class="code-snippet">
            <pre><code>// Pseudocode for a trampoline pattern
function trampoline(fn) {
    while (typeof fn === 'function') {
        fn = fn();
    }
    return fn;
}

function recursiveFunctionThunk(n, acc) {
    if (n === 0) return acc;
    return () => recursiveFunctionThunk(n - 1, acc * n); // Returns a function
}

// Usage:
// const result = trampoline(recursiveFunctionThunk(5, 1));</code></pre>
        </div>
        <p>While more advanced, trampolines are a clever way to handle deep recursion in environments without guaranteed TCO.</p>

        <p>In summary, while recursion is a powerful tool for elegant problem-solving, it's crucial to be mindful of its memory implications and the potential for stack overflow. Understanding these limits and knowing how to apply iterative or other advanced techniques is a fundamental skill for any developer.</p>
    </div>

    <script>
        const canvas = document.getElementById('fractalCanvas');
        const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
        const depthSlider = document.getElementById('depthSlider');
        const depthValueSpan = document.getElementById('depthValue');

        // Initial canvas setup
        const CANVAS_WIDTH = canvas.width;
        const CANVAS_HEIGHT = canvas.height;
        const START_BRANCH_LENGTH = 120; // Initial length of the trunk
        const ANGLE_VARIATION = Math.PI / 6; // Angle for branches (30 degrees)
        const LENGTH_DECREASE_FACTOR = 0.75; // How much each new branch shrinks
        const STROKE_COLOR = '#4a2c0f'; // Dark brown for branches
        const LEAF_COLOR = '#228B22'; // Forest green for leaves
        const LEAF_SIZE = 5;

        // Function to clear the canvas and draw the tree
        function drawTree() {
            ctx.clearRect(0, 0, CANVAS_WIDTH, CANVAS_HEIGHT); // Clear canvas
            ctx.fillStyle = '#fdfdfd'; // Light background for the tree area
            ctx.fillRect(0, 0, CANVAS_WIDTH, CANVAS_HEIGHT);

            const currentDepth = parseInt(depthSlider.value);
            depthValueSpan.textContent = currentDepth;

            ctx.save(); // Save the initial canvas state (no transformations yet)

            // Move origin to the bottom center of the canvas
            ctx.translate(CANVAS_WIDTH / 2, CANVAS_HEIGHT);

            // Start drawing the main trunk
            // Parameters: length, angle (relative to current orientation), current depth, max depth
            drawBranch(START_BRANCH_LENGTH, -Math.PI / 2, 0, currentDepth); // -PI/2 for upward direction

            ctx.restore(); // Restore to the initial canvas state
        }

        // Recursive function to draw a branch
        // length: current branch length
        // angle: current angle of the branch relative to the canvas's X-axis
        // currentDepth: how many levels deep we are in the recursion
        // maxDepth: the user-defined maximum recursion depth
        function drawBranch(length, angle, currentDepth, maxDepth) {
            if (currentDepth >= maxDepth) {
                // Base case: If max depth is reached, draw a 'leaf' (a small circle)
                // This prevents infinite recursion.
                ctx.beginPath();
                ctx.arc(0, -length, LEAF_SIZE, 0, Math.PI * 2); // Draw a circle at the end of the branch
                ctx.fillStyle = LEAF_COLOR;
                ctx.fill();
                return;
            }

            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(0, 0); // Start at the current origin
            ctx.lineTo(0, -length); // Draw line upwards (because Y-axis is inverted for drawing)
            ctx.strokeStyle = STROKE_COLOR;
            ctx.lineWidth = Math.max(1, (maxDepth - currentDepth) * 1.5); // Thicker branches at lower depth
            ctx.stroke();

            // Move to the end of the drawn branch
            ctx.translate(0, -length);

            // Recursively draw two new branches
            // Save context before drawing left branch
            ctx.save();
            ctx.rotate(ANGLE_VARIATION); // Rotate for the left branch
            drawBranch(length * LENGTH_DECREASE_FACTOR, angle + ANGLE_VARIATION, currentDepth + 1, maxDepth);
            ctx.restore(); // Restore context to position after drawing the current branch

            // Save context before drawing right branch
            ctx.save();
            ctx.rotate(-ANGLE_VARIATION); // Rotate for the right branch
            drawBranch(length * LENGTH_DECREASE_FACTOR, angle - ANGLE_VARIATION, currentDepth + 1, maxDepth);
            ctx.restore(); // Restore context to position after drawing the current branch

            // Move back to the start of the current branch (before its children were drawn)
            // This is crucial for the next iteration of the parent branch's drawing
            ctx.translate(0, length);
        }

        // Event listener for the slider
        depthSlider.addEventListener('input', drawTree);

        // Initial draw when the page loads
        drawTree();

    </script>

</body>
</html>
```

