        <h3>What is Recursion?</h3>
        <p>Recursion is a programming technique where a function calls itself to solve a problem. It breaks down a complex problem into smaller, identical subproblems. A recursive function typically has two parts:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Base Case:</strong> A condition that stops the recursion, preventing an infinite loop.</li>
            <li><strong>Recursive Step:</strong> The part where the function calls itself with a modified input, moving closer to the base case.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>In our fractal tree example, the base case is when the <code>depth</code> reaches 0 (or less), and the recursive step is drawing two smaller branches for each larger branch.</p>

        <h3>The Call Stack</h3>
        <p>When a function is called, information about that function's execution (its local variables, parameters, and the point to return to) is pushed onto a data structure called the <strong>call stack</strong>. This stack operates on a Last-In, First-Out (LIFO) principle. When a function finishes executing, its information is popped off the stack.</p>

        <h3>Recursion Depth Limits</h3>
        <p>Every time a recursive function calls itself, a new "stack frame" is pushed onto the call stack. This consumes a small amount of memory. Operating systems and JavaScript engines (like V8 in Chrome) impose a limit on the maximum size of the call stack to prevent programs from consuming all available memory or getting stuck in infinite loops.</p>
        <p>This limit varies by browser and environment, but for JavaScript in browsers, it's typically in the range of a few thousands to tens of thousands of calls. For instance, you might find limits around 10,000 to 100,000 for simple recursive calls, but complex functions with many local variables will hit the limit sooner.</p>

        <h3>Stack Overflow Errors</h3>
        <p>A <strong>"Stack Overflow" error</strong> occurs when a program attempts to push more stack frames onto the call stack than the system's allocated limit allows. This commonly happens in recursive functions that:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Lack a proper base case:</strong> Leading to infinite recursion.</li>
            <li><strong>Have a base case that is never reached:</strong> Similar to the above.</li>
            <li><strong>Require a very deep recursion:</strong> Even with a correct base case, if the problem naturally requires more recursive calls than the stack limit permits (e.g., trying to process an extremely long linked list recursively).</li>
        </ul>
        <p>When a stack overflow occurs, the program usually crashes or throws an error, indicating that it ran out of stack space.</p>

        <h3>Practical Solutions to Deep Recursion</h3>
        <p>While recursion is elegant, especially for problems like tree traversals or fractals, it's crucial to be aware of its limitations. Here are common strategies to avoid stack overflow when deep recursion is a concern:</p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <strong>Iterative Solutions:</strong> Many recursive algorithms can be rewritten iteratively using loops (<code>for</code>, <code>while</code>) and explicit data structures like stacks or queues. This is often the most robust solution for very deep problems as it avoids the call stack limit.
                <p><em>Example:</em> Tree traversals (pre-order, in-order, post-order) can be done iteratively with an explicit stack.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Tail Call Optimization (TCO):</strong> Some programming languages and environments can optimize "tail calls." A tail call is a function call that is the very last operation performed by a function. If a recursive call is a tail call, the compiler/interpreter can reuse the current stack frame instead of creating a new one, effectively eliminating stack growth.
                <p><strong>Note for JavaScript:</strong> While ES6 technically included TCO, most major JavaScript engines (V8, SpiderMonkey, Chakra) have not implemented it due to various complexities and debugging challenges. Therefore, you generally cannot rely on TCO in JavaScript for preventing stack overflows.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Memoization/Dynamic Programming:</strong> For problems with overlapping subproblems (e.g., Fibonacci sequence), memoization (caching results of expensive function calls) can drastically reduce the number of recursive calls, though it doesn't directly solve the depth issue if the recursion is inherently deep.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Adjusting Stack Limits (Advanced/Not Recommended for Web):</strong> In some environments (e.g., Node.js), you can sometimes increase the stack size limit (e.g., <code>node --stack-size=20000 script.js</code>). However, this is generally not feasible or recommended for browser-based JavaScript as you have no control over the user's browser settings.
            </li>
        </ol>
        <p>For our fractal tree, a depth of 12 is well within safe limits. However, imagine if you tried to draw a tree with a depth of 10,000 – that would almost certainly trigger a stack overflow error!</p>
